<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="295" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1046,1325]" pageId="5" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1047,1073]" pageId="5" pageNumber="295">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific name of the new species is Latin, meaning „razor“. The name relates to the extremely thin distal part of the median lobe in ventral view—sharp like a razor! It is a noun in the nominative singular stand- ing in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="295" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1046,1325]" pageId="5" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,294,1155,1181]" pageId="5" pageNumber="295">Ecology</emphasis>
: The 
<typeStatus box="[360,458,1154,1180]" pageId="5" pageNumber="295">holotype</typeStatus>
was found on a steep slope in a beech forest when collecting 
<taxonomicName box="[1158,1312,1154,1180]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="295" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Staphylinidae</taxonomicName>
species by sifting almost dry or slightly moisty material from the ground. The collectors do not remember a closely situated brook or any other water or wet ground. Possibly, the specimen was crawling over the ground searching for a new locality. The collector reported that it is rare but not unusual that Hydradephaga are found in sifted material (see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Balke, M. &amp; Hendrich, L." box="[151,423,1298,1325]" pageId="5" pageNumber="295" pagination="91 - 99" refId="ref3048" refString="Balke, M. &amp; Hendrich, L. (1996) A new species of the terrestrial water beetle genus Geodessus Brancucci (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae), sieved from leaf litter in southern India. Aquatic Insects, 18 (2), 91 - 99. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650429609361607" type="journal article" year="1996">Balke &amp; Hendrich 1996</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
